content.thinking:
OK, let me look at the D2 AIM_FOLLOW_PATH case more carefully. There's a difference in the anger_level calculation:

C (lines 1507-1513):
```c
int anger_level = 65;
if (aip->behavior == AIB_STATION)
    if (Point_segs[aip->hide_index + aip->path_length - 1].segnum == aip->hide_segment) {
        anger_level = 64;
    }
```

OCaml (lines 2171-2172):
```ocaml
let anger_level = ref 65 in


if !behavior = aib_station then anger_level := 64;
```

The OCaml version unconditionally sets anger_level to 64 for station robots, whereas the C version only does this when the path endpoint matches the hide segment. This is a meaningful difference, but I can't reconcile it without access to the Point_segs data structure. Now I'm checking the AIM_STILL case to see how it's handled in both versions.

